    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if we're strictly talking about what qualifies as an encroachment, does the code allow for things like signage or awnings to extend into the setback, or is that an automatic violation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Signage and awnings extending into the setback zone are usually treated with the same level of scrutiny as a structural encroachment, though sometimes the code has specific carve-outs for commercial visibility. It's not always an *automatic* violation, but it's definitely a high-risk area, especially when you're dealing with a corner lot where visibility is key.\n\nIf the code doesn't explicitly permit it, then yes, it's a violation. The city wants to maintain the established streetscape and the required open space. It’s a constant battle, really, trying to keep the storefront looking good while staying within the lines.\n\nAwnings, for instance, can be tricky because they are often considered part of the building's facade, but if they jut out past the required line, they become an encroachment. It’s a classic case of a small, shiny piece of metal that decides it wants to take up more space than it should. I always tell my clients, \"Don't let your signage become a rogue piece of debris; it'll attract the wrong kind of attention.\"",
      "source": "target",
